        <div n="Z66537L1" type="poem"><head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-headnote-1"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-headnote-2"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-headnote-3"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head>
      <lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-line-1"><hi rend="display-initial">T<hi rend="SMALL-CAPS">O</hi></hi> Madness, S<hi rend="SMALL-CAPS">WIFT</hi> bequeaths his whole estate;</l><l n="2" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-line-2"> Why should we wonder? S<hi rend="SMALL-CAPS">WIFT</hi> is right in that:</l><l n="3" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-line-3"> For 'tis a rule, as all our lawyers know,</l><l n="4" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-line-4"> Men's fortune to the next of kin should go;</l><l n="5" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-line-5"> And 'tis as sure, unless old bards have ly'd,</l><l n="6" xml:id="spp-Z66537L1-line-6"> Great Wits to Madness are most near ally'd.Z66537L1   </l></lg></div>
